<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,758,1647]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1514,1539]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[323,488,1514,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Shortcrowna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrostriata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[323,488,1514,1539]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. rubrostriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[496,584,1515,1538]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
externally resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Li" authorityName="Li &amp; Li" authorityYear="2014" box="[833,1095,1514,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Shortcrowna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leishanensis">
<emphasis box="[833,999,1514,1539]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. leishanensis</emphasis>
Li &amp; Li
</taxonomicName>
in coloration and keys to that species in Li &amp; Li's (2014) key. It can be differentiated by the absence of well defined black round spots on the face and by the more acutely pointed posterior lobe of the male pygofer (
<figureCitation box="[920,1029,1586,1611]" captionStart="FIGURES40" captionStartId="74.[151,264,1844,1867]" captionTargetBox="[187,1428,224,1800]" captionTargetId="figure@74.[157,1430,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURES40 A–G. Shortcrowna rubrostriatasp.nov. A.Pygofer, lateral view.B. Style, dorsalview; C. Style, lateral view; D. Subgenital plate, ventral view; E.Connective,dorsal view; F. Aedeagus, lateral view; G.Aedeagus, posteroventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1195970/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 40 A</figureCitation>
) compared to the conically rounded posterior lobe of the pygofer in the latter species (
<bibRefCitation box="[708,949,1622,1647]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref34555" refString="Li, Y. &amp; Li, Z. Z. (2014) Shortcrowna, a new genus of Evacanthinae (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae) from China. Zootaxa, 3764 (4), 467 - 474. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3764.4.6" type="journal article">Li &amp; Li 2014, fig. 29</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
